accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs our increasingly globalized world alters the dynamics of migration, the ideas that migrants have about returning to their home countries have evolved as well. This diverse collection examines the changes and complexities of migration patterns in a range of Asian countries and cities, exploring how globalization and transnationalism shape and give meaning to the migrant experience. From Japanese-Brazilian transmigrants and Filipina students in Ireland to skilled migrants from India, the authors address migrants' backgrounds, ambitions, and opportunities to offer intriguing insights and propose fascinating new questions about the lives of migrants in today's world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEmigration and immigration. 0aReturn migrationzAsia. 0aReturn migration. 4aAsian Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aTransnationalism, migration, Asia.1 aAnwar, Nausheen H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaas, Michiel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhatt, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaibara, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoh, Priscilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNguyen, Cindy A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNititham, Diane Sabenacio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 avon Baeyer, Sarah LeBaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060651508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Back